==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tithe
<hw>Tithe</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>tithe</ets>,
<ets>tethe</ets>, properly an adj., tenth, AS. <ets>te⟦oacute⟧<?/a</ets>
the tenth; akin to <ets>ti⟦eacute⟧n</ets>, <ets>t<?/n</ets>,
<ets>t⟦emac⟧n</ets>, ten, G. <ets>zehnte</ets>, adj., tenth, n., a
tithe, Icel. <ets>t⟦imac⟧und</ets> the tenth; tithe, Goth.
<ets>ta⟦iacute⟧hunda</ets> tenth. See <er>Ten</er>, and cf.
<er>Tenth</er>, <er>Teind</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A tenth; the
tenth part of anything; specifically, the tenthpart of the increase
arising from the profits of land and stock, allotted to the clergy for
their support, as in England, or devoted to religious or charitable
uses. Almost all the <xex>tithes</xex> of England and Wales are commuted
by law into rent charges.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>tithes</qex> of the corn, the new wine, and the oil.</q>
<rj><qau>Neh. xiii. 5.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Tithes</xex> are called <xex>personal</xex> when
accuring from labor, art, trade, and navigation; <xex>predial</xex>,
when issuing from the earth, as hay, wood, and fruit; and
<xex>mixed</xex>, when accuring from beaste fed from the ground.</note>
<rj><au>Blackstone.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, a small part or proportion.</def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Great tithes</b></col>, <cd>tithes of corn, hay, and
wood.</cd> -- <col><b>Mixed tithes</b></col>, <cd>tithes of wool, milk,
pigs, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Small tithes</b></col>, <cd>personal and
mixed tithes.</cd> -- <col><b>Tithe commissioner</b></col>, <cd>one of a
board of officers appointed by the government for arranging propositions
for commuting, or compounding for, tithes.</cd> <mark>[Eng.]</mark>
<au>Simmonds.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tithe</ent>⟦br⟧

